    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Dangerous Movies?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert W Kubey letter on Sept 14 article deplores marketing aimed at attracting young children to violent films</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Parties Share Soapbox in Hearing to Scold Hollywood'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Two Parties Share Soapbox in Hearing to Scold Hollywood'' (front page, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>Jack Valenti, the chief lobbyist for the movie industry, promised that movie executives who avoided the hearings on Wednesday would appear in two weeks when the Senate Commerce Committee reconvened its hearings on the marketing of violent media products to children. One wonders how these executives will defend the practice of including action figures of characters from PG-13 movies with the children's meals given to 4-year-olds at fast-food restaurants.</p>
        <p>This practice is extraordinarily effective at increasing a child's wish to see a movie with a rating deemed inappropriate for his age. Don't the film and fast-food industries together undermine parents and the movie-ratings system when they deliberately attract under-age children to inappropriate films?</p>
        <p>ROBERT W. KUBEY  Highland Park, N.J., Sept. 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer, a developmental psychologist, directs the Center for Media Studies at Rutgers University.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
